body:
Vanilla models can override parent texture attributes. However, Forge's multi-layer models do not support this functionality. If you want to override a texture in a parent layer, you can't. Here's an example drawn out in JSON.

# Parent

```json
{
  "parent": "minecraft:block/block",
  "loader": "forge:multi-layer",
  "layers": {
    "solid": {
      "textures": {
        "particle": "example:blocks/exampletex"
      },
      "elements": [
        {
          "name": "partExample",
          "from": [10.8, 1, 10.8],
          "to": [11.8, 9, 11.8],
          "rotation": { "angle": 0, "axis": "z", "origin": [0, 9, 0] },
          "faces": {
            "north": { "uv": [13.5, 7, 14, 11], "texture": "#particle" },
            "east": { "uv": [13, 7, 13.5, 11], "texture": "#particle" },
            "south": { "uv": [14.5, 7, 15, 11], "texture": "#particle" },
            "west": { "uv": [14, 7, 14.5, 11], "texture": "#particle" },
            "up": { "uv": [14, 7, 13.5, 6.5], "texture": "#particle" },
            "down": { "uv": [14.5, 6.5, 14, 7], "texture": "#particle" }
          }
        }
      ]
    }
  }
}
```

# Child

```json
{
  "parent": "minecraft:block/block",
  "loader": "forge:multi-layer",
  "layers": {
    "solid": {
      "parent": "example:block/parent",
      "textures": {
        "particle": "example:blocks/exampletex2"
      }
    }
  }
}
```

If a block were to have the `Child` model, it would still have `exampletex`, and not the expected override of `exampletex2`.
